{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 20:25:34.077485", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall health: Healthy. No reachability failures, no clear control-plane faults observed.\n- Data plane: End-to-end IPv4 connectivity between hosts is working with 0% loss and low RTTs.\n- Control plane: All EBGP sessions across leaves, spines, and super-spine are Established and exchanging expected prefixes. Routing tables contain the expected /24 host networks and /31 interconnects. ECMP is present on spines toward super-spine; leaves appear to install a single best path per prefix (typical).\n- No faulty devices identified. No root cause for failure as no anomaly was detected.\n\nKey observations and evidence\n\n1) Host connectivity and L3 edge configuration\n- pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2/24, default 10.0.0.1) and pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2/24, default 10.0.1.1) have correct addressing and default gateways.\n- Reachability tests:\n  - pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: 0% loss, avg RTT ~3.75 ms.\n  - Multiple other host pairs (across pods) show 0% loss and low RTTs (≈1–5 ms), indicating fabric-wide reachability is normal.\n\n2) EBGP control-plane health\n- leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200): 4 EBGP neighbors (spines) up; each reports State/PfxRcd 7–8; sends 8 prefixes. Routing table:\n  - Connected: 10.0.0.0/24 (leaf local).\n  - Learns 10.0.1.0/24 and other leaf subnets via spine neighbors.\n  - Learns 10.1.x/24 via alternate spine neighbor.\n- leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201): Mirror of above, with 10.0.1.0/24 connected and the other subnets learned via spines.\n- spine_router_0_0 (AS 65100) and spine_router_0_1 (AS 65101): 6 neighbors each (2 super-spine links + 4 leaf peers). Both show:\n  - All EBGP neighbors Established.\n  - 10.1.x/24 installed with dual next-hops via two super-spine interfaces (ECMP visible as two installed paths).\n  - 10.0.x/24 learned from respective leaves.\n- super_spine_router_0 (AS 65000): 8 EBGP neighbors Established (multiple spines across pods). Routing table shows:\n  - 10.0.x/24 learned via a specific spine neighbor (e.g., 172.16.0.5).\n  - 10.1.x/24 learned via another spine neighbor (e.g., 172.16.0.9).\n  - Note: Selection appears single-best for each group of prefixes (no ECMP shown here), which is acceptable and not an error.\n\n3) Routing/FIB sanity\n- All routers have complete coverage for the relevant host subnets (10.0.{0,1}.0/24 at minimum) and the necessary interconnect /31s are present as connected routes.\n- Spines show ECMP up to super-spine; leaves select one best path per prefix, which is common with EBGP without multipath configuration.\n- BGP session uptimes (~00:00:30–00:00:36) suggest recent initialization but stable operation.\n\nPotential discrepancies (non-impacting)\n- The provided “Topology” lists leaf-to-host interfaces as eth2, but the live routing tables on leaves indicate the host-facing subnets are on eth4 (e.g., C>* 10.0.0.0/24 … eth4; C>* 10.0.1.0/24 … eth4). This looks like documentation vs. implementation interface numbering drift, not a functional issue.\n- The lab inventory and BGP views include more devices and subnets than the minimal topology description (multiple leaves/spines/pods beyond the two hosts mentioned). This is consistent with a larger Clos fabric and does not indicate a fault.\n\nConclusion\n- Anomaly detection: None observed. Both data and control planes are functioning normally.\n- Fault localization: No faulty devices identified.\n- Root cause: Not applicable; no failure detected.\n\nNotes\n- If strict ECMP across all tiers is a design requirement at the super-spine, current single-best-path selection for 10.0.x/24 and 10.1.x/24 on the super-spine could be considered suboptimal but is not a fault and does not impact reachability based on current evidence.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 11045, "output_tokens": 4002, "total_tokens": 15047, "input_token_details": {"